Riverview Intermediate Unit #6
September 9 at 10:18 AM ·

Guest Teacher Training at RIU6 – Substitutes needed for RIU6 Region Schools

September 15 @ RIU6 from 8-3pm.

If you have a College Degree, an Emergency Teaching Permit can be issued for you to do day to day subbing in our schools as much or as little as needed. This training is a small preparatory program with some virtual videos, lots of paperwork, a few key special education topics, and a $25 processing fee, and you can get your emergency teaching permit to substitute in our schools and make some money on off days or every day as our schools are desperate. Email mlaverde@riu6.org or call 814-297-5103.



Future Training Days:

9/15/20, 11/10/20, 1/26/21, 3/30/21

9/7/21, 11/9/21, 1/25/22, 3/29/22

post_text: What a great opening day for our faculty and staff ! Ben Webber, an OCHS graduate and 13 time Emmy winner at ESPN, conducted our opening day presentation. He invited a special guest, Tom Rinaldi, to offer some encouraging words to our educators. We followed with an educational training on sensitivity in the classroom conducted by Jodi Pfarr and ended with a training on trauma informed practices by OCHS graduate Matt LaVerde. What better way to ease our teachers into the new school year than providing desserts offered by Little Orphan Annie’s Ice Cream Truck. We are excited for the start of our school year ! #oilerstogether

post_text: Congratulations to Mario Fontanazza, a senior at OCHS. He set two WORLD RECORDS in an ADAU 100% Raw Powerlifting Meet. Aside from his athletic accomplishments, Mario is also one of the top students in his class academically! #studentathlete

Janelle Hall WTAE
July 29 at 5:49 PM ·

PIAA: NO SPECTATORS AT HIGH SCHOOL GAMES
"Right now we’re anticipating in most of our scenarios, no spectators and that’s going to be a difficult thing."
-- Robert Lombardi, executive director of the PIAA

This news comes as the PIAA just announced today -- the fall sports season can proceed as planned.

In June, PA Governor Tom Wolf said this on Twitter:
"@GovernorTomWolf
Pre-K to 12 School Sports:
Gatherings must be limited to 250 people and the facility as a whole may not exceed 50% of total occupancy.
No entry
No spectators allowed."

https://www.wtae.com/article/piaa-set-to-issue-covid-19-guidelines-for-high-school-football-other-sports/33450010

This news comes as the PIAA just announced today -- the fall sports season can proceed as planned.

In June, PA Governor Tom Wolf said this on Twitter:
"@GovernorTomWolf
Pre-K to 12 School Sports:
Gatherings must be limited to 250 people and the facility as a whole may not exceed 50% of total occupancy.
No entry
No spectators allowed."

We started delivering sensory bags today to local emergency responders. SugarCreek police dept was the first in venango county to receive our sensory bag. Oil City fire dept also received theirs today . The young man pictured is Oil City student Raymond Hinojosa and he is the brain behind the idea. You can see him telling the responders what each item is used for and how it will help in an emergency situation. Our plan is to equip each and every emergency responder in venango county with a sensory bag, our ultimate goal is to provide 1 for every vehicle. If you are a department and would like a bag or know 1 that needs a bag please message us. Thanks for making venango county so much safer!

Attention Oil City High School Community:

During the past few months the district has held out hope that there would be a possibility that a 2020 Oil City Prom could take place. We were optimistic that as time continued to pass the Covid-19 pandemic would be under better control and risks for such an event would lessen. Unfortunately that has not happened and we are now forced to make the sad decision to cancel the Jr. / Sr. Prom.

The Oil City Area School District is committed to the safety and well being of all our students and staff. It is with that in mind that we have made the decision to cancel this year’s prom (2020) that was rescheduled to take place in August.

post_text: This post is for the purpose of updating families on when P-EBT benefits will be issued and received. Some households are beginning to receive their cards in the mail already. Do not throw away the card. Most students will have $370 on the card. All you have to do is activate the card. All students in our district will receive a card, regardless of income, with the exception of families that receive SNAP or TANF. Those familes should have already had their benefits issued to their EBT card. If not, you may submit an inquiry at https://www.emergencymealsurvey.com/PA. All others, cards are in the process of being issued and mailed, but due to the very large volume, the timeline varies. Households should receive their cards by the end of July.

post_text:
2020 National Choral Award
May 27, 2020
The National Choral Award is given to the outstanding graduating senior who has contributed most to his or her musical organization during their school music career. All members of the high school choirs vote for their selection based on the following points:

1. Better than average scholastic standing
2. Cooperation above and beyond normal duties
3. General Musicianship
4. Music Performance
5. Attendance at concerts/extra events
6. Desire to improve and take criticism
7. Diligence
8. Selflessness
9. Personal Integrity
10. Qualified to carry on the best traditions of the school

While all of our seniors have exhibited these qualities throughout their high school careers, we can only choose one.

It is my pleasure to announce that the 2020 National School Choral Award Recipient is... KATIE FYE

post_text: Senior Spotlight - Sarah Teeter is the daughter of Tim and Peg Teeter. Sarah was named to the Principal's List during every quarter of her high school career. She is a member of the National Honor Society, and served on Leadership Council, World Affairs Council, and was a Global Leadership Ambassador. She was also a member of the soccer team and helped in the writing lab. Outside of school, Sarah is a pianist. Sarah's future plans include attending RIT to receive a Master’s degree in Biochemistry. post_text:
Starting June 3rd...

The County is taking over meal delivery from the schools with our first distribution date of June 3, 2020. Meals will be distributed at times and sites listed on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday each week. Each bag will contain breakfast and lunch items for multiple days. We will not be providing breakfast or lunch for Saturdays or Sundays, only the week days. There will be no home deliveries of meals. Someone must go to one of the locations listed to receive their meal bags, the child/children do not need to be present.

OCASD Seniors have the opportunity to contribute to a virtual yearbook offered by Seven Mountains Media. According to the company, there is no cost to add or view content.
Note: This yearbook does not take the place of the Oil City Yearbook. It is simply an offer from Virtual Yearbook 2020 to participate in another way to share and view memories.

Please contact daniel@7mountainsmedia.com with any questions.

The virtual yearbook is what you would expect from a yearbook, but in an e-book, interactive format. Each local school will have their devoted section. Students, parents, educators and coaches can upload content and we will format it into a special recognition for the class of 2020.

Seniors can upload pictures, videos, audio messages, poems and more. Be Creative!

Submissions are now being accepted at virtualyearbook2020.com

Please contact daniel@7mountainsmedia.com with any questions.

post_text: Senior Spotlight - Kathryn Fye is the daughter of Beth Fye and Stephen Fye. Katie participated in A Cappella, Rhapsody in Blues, and the Treble Choir. She attended district choir several years earning 10th, 4th, and 2nd chairs and moved on to regions to earn a 9th chair. Another highlight of Katie’s vocal career has been her involvement in the quartets. The past two summers Katie and her quartet had the opportunity to travel to Oklahoma and Manchester, England to compete in the Rising Star. At both competitions, they placed in the top ten in the world. Katie has also played in the marching band (drum leader this past season), performed in the musicals, was a member of Broadcasting, and the Bowling club. This fall Katie plans to attend Youngstown State University to major in Music Education.

We'd like to share some positive news from the past week that's happened at OCASD:

*Students of all ages, including Kindergarten, were able to reconnect with their teachers and classmates via Zoom.

*Sarah Fisher was accepted into the prestigious Governor's School for Sciences at Carnegie Mellon University.

*8th Grade WEB Leaders held their own Zoom meetings with their 6th graders to do an at-home scavenger hunt in an effort to reach out to their classmates and offer any help they may need.

This morning, Governor Wolf issued an order under Act 13 of 2020 to close all public schools through the end of the 2019-2020 academic year, as defined by the local school calendar.

Additionally, Governor Wolf is ordering all K-12 schools and programs, public and private, to be closed through the end of the 2019-2020 academic year. Pennsylvania Pre-K Counts, Head Start Supplemental Assistance Programs and Preschool Early Intervention programs will also remain closed, and institutions of higher education are prohibited from offering in-person instruction.

post_text:
Breakfast and Lunch for Students:
Starting Tuesday, March 17th the OCASD will be providing free lunch and breakfast to students. Any student that is 18 years old or younger may visit one of the following locations: Oil City Senior High School (cafeteria entrance) or Seventh Street Elementary (cafeteria/gymnasium entrance) to pick up a bagged meal. The bagged meal will contain lunch and breakfast for the following day. The window for pick up will be from 11:30-12:30 daily (Monday-Friday). Students must be present in order to pick up the meals. This will be similar to a "drive through/take out" service. Families may transport their children and/or age appropriate students may walk to the locations. The buildings will be closed and the bathroom facilities will not be open to the public. If any family is having difficulty accessing one of these locations, please private message this page in order to make alternate arrangements. It is our hope that this service will help alleviate any hardships that the school closure may have on our families.

post_text: The 8th grade WEB leaders got together last week for some bowling fun. They have been working so hard at their important role at the middle school. WEB is a mentoring program where 8th graders help out all of our 6th graders with various things in and out of school. Every spring, 7th graders may choose to apply and interview to earn their role as WEB Leaders for their entire 8th grade year. After some extensive training in the summer, they are assigned a small group of 6th graders to look after. They work with their 6th graders on being organized, keeping up with their grades, general tips for success, healthy relationships, and so much more. If you know an 8th grade WEB leader, please thank them for their commitment to helping others!

shared_text:
Oil City High School Swim Team is with Emily Coxson.
February 6 at 11:17 PM ·

Whoa, we did it! The Oil City girls capped off a perfect season (15-0) tonight by beating Grove City 96-74. It is the first league title since 1973 for the girl’s team, and we believe the first undefeated season perhaps since then. Coach Charlie created a perfect line up, but GC didn’t go quietly, GC coach threw a good line up and we had to withstand the waves of talented swimmers one after another. But, in the end the Oilers came through. The girls also broke a pool record tonight that was set in 1996 by Warren. Morgan Stover, Emily Russell, Christina Smith and Christa Schneider posted a 1:43.85 topping the previous 1:44.56. And, we added a new district qualifier in walk on swimmer Ronni Hammerly, well done!
The fellas faded into the background tonight, but they too closed out the regular season with a win closing the regular season with a 13-2 record. 28-2 combined record is AWESOME!!! Coaches are so proud to wear Blue and White. Next up, the inaugural Region Cup meet at Grove City College on Saturday - GO OILERS! #oilcityswimming #oilerswimming #undefeatedseason

post_text: OCHS students participated in the 20th Annual Tri-State Honor Band at Mercyhurst University this past weekend. Our own Dan Cartwright helped prepare the students for their concerts. He conducted a song during the performance.

post_text: Congratulations on an outstanding jr high cross country season. The boys were the region champions, the region invitational champions, 3rd at Macquaid (biggest invite on the east coast), and 2nd at the Rocky Grove invitational. The girls were 2nd at Mcquaid, runner up in the region and 3rd and Rocky Grove. Kennedy Liederbach was the girls overall region champion.

post_text:
Do you need help in completing your FAFSA form?

Seniors and Parents
FAFSA Completion Workshop
Sponsored by ETS of Clarion Univ.
CLASS OF 2020
Saturday, November 9, 2019
Cranberry High School— Library
9:00 AM —11:00 AM

Bring your income information (2018 tax documents), asset information, social security numbers, driver’s license and your questions to receive assistance in completing your FAFSA. Computers will be available for online filing.

The FAFSA deadline for Pennsylvania is May 1, and many schools have earlier deadlines for institutional aid. A PHEAA representative will be available to answer questions and help you file your FAFSA.

Pre-registration is required. Call the Educational Talent Search office at Clarion Univ. at 1-888-533-6487 or 814-393-2071 to register. Please note there may be limited space available, so

Note: Please obtain an FSA ID for the filer (student) and the parent at FSAID.ed.gov before the session. This will save you time!

post_text: Hats off to Mr. Stahl, Mrs. Curran, teachers, faculty and community organizations on the successful first Find Your Future Day. In addition to providing students with opportunities to see the VTC, Venango Campus, 5 local businesses and a Military training facility our students took the ASVAB, PSAT and SAT tests today to assist them in making decisions that will impact their futures. Some of our students participated in community service opportunities and job shadows.
